<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="21" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gómez-Zapata &amp; Haelewaters &amp; Quijada &amp; Pfister &amp; Aime" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Gómez-Zapata &amp; Haelewaters &amp; Quijada &amp; Pfister &amp; Aime" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Hemiphacidiaceae" genus="Cenangium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cenangium colensoi" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Cenangium colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is described from dead leaves of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Cordyline" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cordyline" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Cordyline</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Cordyline" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="order">Asparagales</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Cordyline" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Asparagaceae</taxonomicName>
) in New Zealand (
<bibRefCitation author="Hooker, JD" journalOrPublisher="Lovell Reeve, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B46" refString="Hooker, JD, 1855. The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H.M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839-1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants. Lovell Reeve, London" title="The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H. M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839 - 1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants." year="1855">Hooker 1855</bibRefCitation>
). The host had been mistakenly reported as 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Phormium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Phormium" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Phormium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Phormium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="order">Asparagales</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asphodelaceae" genus="Phormium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Asphodelaceae</taxonomicName>
) by Berkeley in 
<bibRefCitation author="Hooker, JD" journalOrPublisher="Lovell Reeve, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B46" refString="Hooker, JD, 1855. The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H.M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839-1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants. Lovell Reeve, London" title="The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H. M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839 - 1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants." year="1855">Hooker (1855)</bibRefCitation>
and only recently corrected after re-study of the type collection (
<bibRefCitation author="Landcare Research" journalOrPublisher="Desray, Paris" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" publicationUrl="https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" refId="B65" refString="Landcare Research, 2020. Collection details. Pseudopeziza colensoi (Berk.) Massee (1896) [1895-97]. https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" title="Collection details. Pseudopeziza colensoi (Berk.) Massee (1896) [1895 - 97]." url="https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" year="2020">Landcare Research 2020</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gómez-Zapata &amp; Haelewaters &amp; Quijada &amp; Pfister &amp; Aime" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Gómez-Zapata &amp; Haelewaters &amp; Quijada &amp; Pfister &amp; Aime" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Hemiphacidiaceae" genus="Cenangium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cenangium colensoi" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Cenangium colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was later combined in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fuckel" authorityYear="1870" class="Leotiomycetes" family="Hemiphacidiaceae" genus="Pseudopeziza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Pseudopeziza" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Pseudopeziza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and described in more detail by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" author="Massee, GE" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="463 - 524" refId="B70" refString="Massee, GE, 1896. Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi. Journal of the Linnean Society 31: 463 - 524, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" title="Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" volume="31" year="1896">Massee (1896)</bibRefCitation>
. Both authors commented on the watery-grey disc and brownish receptacle of the apothecia. The apothecia develop among the rigid vascular bundles of the epidermis, first covered by the cuticle, then erumpent and opening by a narrow slit, becoming discoid when mature (
<bibRefCitation author="Hooker, JD" journalOrPublisher="Lovell Reeve, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B46" refString="Hooker, JD, 1855. The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H.M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839-1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants. Lovell Reeve, London" title="The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H. M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839 - 1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants." year="1855">Hooker 1855</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" author="Massee, GE" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="463 - 524" refId="B70" refString="Massee, GE, 1896. Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi. Journal of the Linnean Society 31: 463 - 524, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" title="Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" volume="31" year="1896">Massee 1896</bibRefCitation>
). The habit of this fungus fits well with typical macromorphological features of the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Leotiomycetes" family="Clavicipitaceae" genus="Trochila" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Trochila" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Trochila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- a dark brown to black receptacle, which develops beneath the host tissues and eventually becomes erumpent to expose the hymenium by splitting along radial lines or by its splitting into lobes (von 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoehnel, F von" journalOrPublisher="Annales Mycologici" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="330 - 334" refId="B45" refString="Hoehnel, F von, 1917. Ueber die Gattung Trochila Fries. Annales Mycologici 15: 330 - 334" title="Ueber die Gattung Trochila Fries." volume="15" year="1917">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Höhnel">Hoehnel</normalizedToken>
1917
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0007-1536(64)80002-4" author="Greenhalgh, G" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the British Mycological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="311 - 320" refId="B33" refString="Greenhalgh, G, Morgan-Jones, G, 1964. Some species of Trochila and an undescribed discomycete on leaves of Prunus laurocerasus. Transactions of the British Mycological Society 47: 311 - 320, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/S0007-1536(64)80002-4" title="Some species of Trochila and an undescribed discomycete on leaves of Prunus laurocerasus." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0007-1536(64)80002-4" volume="47" year="1964">Greenhalgh and Morgan-Jones 1964</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dennis, RWG" journalOrPublisher="Cramer, Vaduz, Liechtenstein" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B19" refString="Dennis, RWG, 1978. British Ascomycetes. J. Cramer, Vaduz, Liechtenstein" title="British Ascomycetes. J." year="1978">Dennis 1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Baral, H-O" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B6" refString="Baral, H-O, Marson, G, 2005. In vivo veritas. Over 10000 images of fungi and plants (microscopical drawings, water colour plates, photo macro- &amp; microphotographs), with materials on vital taxonomy and xerotolerance. Ed. 3. Privately distributed DVD-ROM." title="In vivo veritas. Over 10000 images of fungi and plants (microscopical drawings, water colour plates, photo macro- &amp; microphotographs), with materials on vital taxonomy and xerotolerance. Ed. 3. Privately distributed DVD-ROM." year="2005">Baral and Marson 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Microscopically, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. colensoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">P. colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described with a parenchymatous excipulum (angular-globose or isodiametric cells), hyaline under the hymenium and dark brown at the cortex (Berkeley in 
<bibRefCitation author="Hooker, JD" journalOrPublisher="Lovell Reeve, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B46" refString="Hooker, JD, 1855. The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H.M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839-1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants. Lovell Reeve, London" title="The botany of the Antarctic Voyage of H. M. discovery ships Erebus and Terror, in the years 1839 - 1843. II. Flora Novae-Zealandiae. Part II. Flowerless plants." year="1855">Hooker 1855</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" author="Massee, GE" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="463 - 524" refId="B70" refString="Massee, GE, 1896. Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi. Journal of the Linnean Society 31: 463 - 524, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" title="Redescriptions of Berkeley's types of fungi." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00812.x" volume="31" year="1896">Massee 1896</bibRefCitation>
), which is also in agreement with the excipular features of 
<taxonomicName class="Leotiomycetes" family="Clavicipitaceae" genus="Trochila" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Trochila" order="Helotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Trochila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. Finally, the hymenium of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. colensoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">P. colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described as composed of inamyloid, 8-spored asci with elliptical hyaline ascospores and slender paraphyses (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">op. cit.</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
In 2018, P.R. Johnston collected two specimens (PDD:112240, PDD:112242, 
<bibRefCitation author="Landcare Research" journalOrPublisher="Desray, Paris" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" publicationUrl="https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" refId="B65" refString="Landcare Research, 2020. Collection details. Pseudopeziza colensoi (Berk.) Massee (1896) [1895-97]. https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" title="Collection details. Pseudopeziza colensoi (Berk.) Massee (1896) [1895 - 97]." url="https://nzfungi2.landcareresearch.co.nz/default.aspx?selected=NameDetails&amp;TabNum=0&amp;NameId=1CB1B798-36B9-11D5-9548-00D0592D548C" year="2020">Landcare Research 2020</bibRefCitation>
) on leaves of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Cordyline" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cordyline australis" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Cordyline australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Cordyline" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Asparagaceae</taxonomicName>
). The morphology, ecology (host), and locality of these new collections agree with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. colensoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="colensoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">P. colensoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The photographs of both specimens reveal features such as guttules in ascospores and paraphyses, protruding hyaline cells in the cortical layer of the upper flank and margin, and hyaline gelatinized hyphae covering the dark globose-angular cells of the ectal excipulum at the base and lower flanks. The latter excipular feature of the receptacle is reminiscent of 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhuang, WY" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="121 - 124" refId="B108" refString="Zhuang, WY, 1990. Calycellinopsis Xishuangbanna gen. et sp. nov. (Dermateaceae), a petiole-inhabiting fungus from China. Mycotaxon 38: 121 - 124" title="Calycellinopsis Xishuangbanna gen. et sp. nov. (Dermateaceae), a petiole-inhabiting fungus from China." volume="38" year="1990">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Zhuang’s">Zhuang's</normalizedToken>
(1990)
</bibRefCitation>
description of 
